column12: Highly Scalable Internet Protocol-Based Communications System
column13: A highly scalable Internet Protocol (IP) based communications system which provides voice and other communication services to end-users. The instant system incorporates a unique architecture which simplifies scaling of services to hundreds of thousands and even millions of subscribers. The instant system architecture includes a means for directly connecting a plurality of peered service providers thereby obviating the need to move the communications across the PSTN. By bypassing the PSTN, the instant system can leverage the advantages of IP-based networks in meeting subscriber communications needs such as, without limitation, quality of service, service up-time, and advanced feature sets. Bypassing the PSTN also allows the peered partners to negotiate communications rates between themselves, without incurring PSTN carrier fees.

column12: SHROUDED WIND TURBINE SYSTEM WITH YAW CONTROL
column13: A wind energy systems includes a shroud for each turbine. The shroud is adapted to direct and accelerate wind towards the turbine. A strong adaptable support assembly is provided for securing turbines to a structure. An air glide yaw assembly facilitates rotational movement of the structure allowing the turbines to face oncoming wind. The turbine blades are optimized for use with a shroud.

column12: Method of latent fault checking a management network
column13: A method of latent fault checking a management network may include a management bus communicating management data for a computing module on the management network; a management controller managing the computing module; a master management controller operating the management bus; and a buffer module between the management bus and each of the management controller and the master management controller, where the buffer module is coupled to provide isolation for each of the management controller and the master management controller from the management bus. Prior to an active fault in the management network, a latent fault checking module is executed on the buffer module to determine if the latent fault checking module detects a latent fault on the buffer module.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR AUTOMATICALLY VISUALLY POSITIONING TRAIN CAR BEDS
column13: A system and method for automatically positioning a metal coil into a rail car using stereoscopic image processing is presented. A method begins by picking up the metal coil using a hoist of a crane. The metal coil is then moved to a position over a rail car to where the metal coil will be located. At least one stereoscopic photo is taken of a location in the rail car to where the metal coil will be located. The coil is accurately positioned as it is lowered based on data extracted from the stereoscopic photo(s) to determine where the coil is as it is lowered onto the rail car. The picking up the metal coil, the moving the metal coil to a position over a rail car and the lowering the metal coil into the rail car are performed automatically without human involvement.

column12: Device and method for testing crane tong grip strength
column13: A device, system, and method for testing and measuring the grip strength of tongs for a crane system is provided. The device may include a frame body carrying a testing assembly configured to measure the tong grip strength. The system may include the grip strength tester used in conjunction with a crane including an operator tower and a pulley assembly operatively connected to the tongs. The method of use associated with the tong grip strength tester may include the steps of expanding a distance between teeth on the tongs and positioning the teeth adjacent sides of the testing assembly, then closing the tongs thereby clamping teeth to the sides of the testing assembly. Then, the testing assembly measures the compressive force associated with the tongs and registers the compressive force in a computer system to determine whether the grip strength is sufficient to lift a weighted slab of material.

column12: Laser propagation system for irradiating sample in flow stream and method of using same
column13: Aspects of the present disclosure include a system for irradiating a sample in a flowing stream. A system according to certain embodiments includes a light propagator having a first optical fiber operably coupled with a first laser, receiving light from a proximal first laser and transmitting the laser light from a distal end to a first location on a flow stream; and a second optical fiber operably coupled with the second laser, receiving light from the proximal second laser and transmitting the laser light from the distal end to a second location on the flow stream. Methods of irradiating a sample in a flow stream with the target system and detecting light from two or more locations on the irradiated flow stream are also provided.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR SUPPORTING AND MOVING A LONG-SPAN STRUCTURE ON A RAIL SYSTEM
column13: A long-span structure engaged with a plurality of first and second transportation devices for moving the long span structure. The transportation devices travel along parallel, longitudinally-oriented first and second tracks; moving the structure between a first position and a second position. A first region of the structure is fixed to each first transportation device. A second region of the structure is secured to each second transportation device via a bearing assembly. The first and second regions of the structure are laterally spaced apart. When the long-span structure thermally expands or contracts, a slider plate of each bearing assembly moves laterally relative to the rest of the bearing assembly. Growth of the structure in a predictable direction is forced by keeping the first region thereof fixed against lateral movement with the first transportation devices and allowing movement of the second region thereof via the bearing assemblies on the second transportation devices.

column12: ABSCHIRMUNGSVORRICHTUNG.
column13: Each control rod drive in a BWR has a flange assembly comprising a housing flange and mating control rod drive flange joined by bolts as well as a shielding device consisting of a number of shielding members. Each shielding member comprises a non-corrosive metallic cylindrical outer-, annular outer bottom, first cylindrical inner, and annular inner bottom wall. A further annular upper interior wall, second cylindrical inner wall and 2 radial walls of a non-corrosive metallic substance are provided. Shielding material located in partial cylindrical chamber reduces measured radiation dose rate in the under-vessel by at least 10%. When assembled, the shielding members surround and enclose the lower terminus of the control rod drive with an effective amt. of shielding material.

column12: METHOD OF PROVIDING ACCESS TO A SURGICAL OBJECT WHEN PERFORMING PLASMA TRANSURETHRAL ENUCLEATION OF BENIGN PROSTATIC HYPERPLASIA
column13: FIELD: medicine.SUBSTANCE: invention relates to medicine, specifically to urology. At initial stage of prostate enucleation, section of mucous membrane and prostate tissue is made to capsule of prostate from neck of urinary bladder within 1 cm along front surface of prostatic urethra in distal direction. Then, dissection is continued with two incisions along the left and right portions of the prostate in direction of 14 and 22 o'clock points of the conditional clock face to the distal portion of the prostate.EFFECT: method enables maximum preservation of an external sphincter of the urethra in the anterior distal surface, which reduces the risk of developing postoperative stress urinary incontinence, as well as optimality of surgical access to tissues of hyperplastic prostate and their subsequent enucleation by using anatomical landmarks when performing Y-shaped incision – bladder neck, middle urethra, left and right distal parts of prostate lobes – at the first stage of plasma transurethral enucleation.1 cl, 2 ex

column12: METHOD FOR PREVENTING INJURY TO THE EXTERNAL URETHRAL SPHINCTER WHEN PERFORMING TRANSURETHRAL LASER ENUCLEATION OF BENIGN PROSTATIC HYPERPLASIA
column13: FIELD: medicine.SUBSTANCE: invention relates to medicine, namely to operative urology. The operation is performed using a holmium laser fiber by dissecting the mucous membrane of the prostatic urethra and prostate tissue from the apical zone to the bladder neck in the proximal direction along the anterior semicircle to the surgical capsule in the direction of 13 and 23 o'clock of the conventional dial. A triangular area is preserved, including the mucous membrane and underlying tissues of the prostatic urethra along the anterior semicircle of the posterior urethra with the base of the conditional triangle on the bladder neck and the apex at the transverse fibers of the external sphincter.EFFECT: method allows maximally preserving the integrity of the urethral sphincter in the anterior region, thereby eliminating the surgical risk of developing stress urinary incontinence in the postoperative period, as well as creating optimal surgical access to hyperplastic prostate nodes and their subsequent enucleation.1 cl, 2 ex

column12: METHOD FOR PREPARING MONO- AND DI-OLEFINE HYDROCARBONS
column13: A method for the production of mono- and diolefinic hydrocarbons by subjecting paraffinic hydrocarbons to catalytic oxidative dehydrogenation at 400 DEG to 700 DEG in the presence of a catalyst comprising oxygen-containing compounds of molybdenum and magnesium taken in a molybdenum/magnesium atomic ratio of 1:0.9 to 1:357, optional components of said catalyst being oxygen-containing compounds of cobalt, iron, chromium, vanadium, nickel, silicon, antimony, boron, gadolinium, dysprosium, gallium, bismuth, titanium, zirconium or niobium.
